observations.recommendation:
To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommend that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

to conduct risk assessment;
to identify critical processes and functions; 
to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 
to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We recommended that Management:

Immediately send a demand letter to the erring contractor as a final warning and require them to complete the works in accordance to the agreed terms and conditions of the contract without prejudice on the computation and imposition of liquidated damages to the said project;

In case of inexcusable failure or negligence of the erring contractor to comply on the above recommendation, the Chief Executive Office shall issue a Notice to Terminate Contract without prejudice to other courses of action and remedies available under the circumstances;

Recover/deduct the unperformed works amounting ₱1,746,397.18 from any payments due to the erring contractor;

Initiate take-over of the remaining work by administration or to consider rebidding through competitive bidding or any of the applicable alternative methods of procurement in accordance with R.A. 9184 and its IRR; and,

The Project Engineers to strictly monitor and supervise the infrastructure projects implemented by this Municipality to prevent time lag and delays.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
Provide the Municipal Accountant copies of pertinent documents such as Project/Program Guidelines, MOA, Ordinances, Operations Manual and Project Status Report on funds received necessary in the conduct analysis of the Due to LGUs and Due to NGAs accounts;
Based on the result of analysis of the Due to LGUs and Due to NGAs accounts, the Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary entries to correct errors and properly classify accounts;
The Municipal Accountant locate and send confirmation letters to identifiable listed government agencies in the Due to LGUs and Due to NGAs to validate if said amounts are due to them by the Municipality. Require said government agencies to execute duly notarized affidavits on the amounts due to them and/or to submit necessary documents, if none are in the custody of the accounting office, as evidence on the part of management for the extent of validation made on the accounts and as proof on the existence of the recorded liability;
Determine and identify, based on available records and thru confirmation with various agencies, the source agencies of the subject unutilized balances and process immediately the return of the unutilized balances of fund transfers to concerned source agencies and/or to the National Treasury, as applicable;
Identify the focal persons responsible for those PPAs whose status of completion is unknown to verify the actual status of its implementation and for them to provide the necessary documentation that will be used as basis for its liquidation and in the recording in the books by the Municipal Accountant; and
Review various programs of the LGU which were recorded under the Due to LGU account but in substance were maintained as trust liability or for safekeeping only to validate its propriety,  particularly on the following: (1) Use of Heavy Equipment by barangays, (2) Imposition of fees from motorcycle operators not recorded as income, (3) Funds received from barangays for safekeeping purposes; and (4) Payment received for the equity portion of the availed socialized economic housing unit.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Accountant submit copy of the JEVs and its supporting documents on the adjustments for the two stale checks (Check Nos. 1255869 and 1256172) made after the books of the LGU for CY 2024 were closed;
The Municipal Treasurer determine the status of the Stale Checks and prepare a report showing as to whether the checks were already claimed by the payee or are still unreleased and on hand;
The Municipal Treasurer send written communication to the concerned payee informing him/her on the status of the check. If the concerned payee appeared to claim the check or requested for a re-issuance of the stale check, the Municipal Treasurer issue a new check to the claimant in accordance with the procedures provided under Section 59 of COA Circular No. 2002-003 on Spoiled and Stale Checks; and
After exhaustion of the communication phase and the check still remained unclaimed in the possession of the Municipal Treasurer, the latter submit the necessary documents to the Municipal Accountant for the recording of the corresponding payable.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Collecting Officers concerned to immediately settle their under/over-remittances, submit written justification and ensure adherence to the existing rules and regulations on the receipt and remittance/deposit of all collections handled by them to prevent loss and/or misuse of government funds and avoid possible shortage in audit, which have penal sanctions;
The Liquidating Officer and the Municipal Treasurer to perform adequate verification and review procedures, including the re-computation of actual collections and remittances, to ensure the accuracy and reliability of information presented in the RCDs. Return the RCD to the concerned collecting officer if discrepancy/ies are noted;
The Municipal Treasurer ensure that proper review and verification is made on all RCDs submitted by collecting officers to check if amount remitted actually coincide with the actual collections as per copies of the issued accountable forms. Constantly remind all accountable officers, including the Liquidating Officer, on the policies concerning collections and remittances; and
The Municipal Accountant coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer in case over/under remittances are noted. For over remittances which may result to cash overage, the amount to be forfeited in favor of the government and recorded as Miscellaneous Income if the overage cannot be satisfactorily explained by the Collecting Officer.

We recommended and Management agreed to ensure that:
The HR:
Require the SB Secretary to submit to her office copies of the minutes of the SB sessions conducted for the Month of April 2024, and the concerned appointed personnel to submit to her office their respective lacking documents pertaining to their attendance for the month of April 2024, such as Approved DTRs, Approved Applications for Leave, Locator Slips or its equivalent, Certificate of Attendance, Copies of Logbook entries and other documents, whichever is applicable, to support the payment of their salary. Consolidate all these documents with attached matrix or summary of information per personnel concerned and submit the same to the Audit Team (Please refer to the attached Appendix E for the lacking documents);
Review the Biometric System particularly for the DTRs of personnel rendering night shift duties for possible adjustments so that the same will be able to reflect the time in and out in the correct column in the DTRs to prevent manual entries and to avoid ambiguity of data. In cases where manual entries cannot be avoided, a duly signed-off certification to that effect be attached to the DTRs and payroll;
Ensure that erasures in the DTR be properly countersigned and manual entries be properly supported by appropriate documents and/or justification on the matter;
Submit to the Audit Team duty schedules of personnel who have different duty time and days other than the regular 8:00 am to 5:00 pm Monday to Friday;
The Municipal Accountant to ensure that:
Payments of salaries of appointed personnel be supported with complete DTRs, approved Application for Leave and other required documents; and
Minutes of SB sessions be attached to the claim of honorarium of elected officials;
Management to implement the use of a logbook for manual entry of attendance in addition to the Biometric System to be used as basis for reconciliation and/or supporting document on the entries in the DTR and as a back-up document in case problems will be encountered with the Biometric System; and
Management to require the use of locator slips or its equivalent with certificate of appearance to support the “no time in/out” in the DTRs of all concerned personnel especially when they are out of their official station without approved travel orders.

We recommended to Management the following:
The GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) prepare the LGU GAD Agenda based on the results of gender analysis conducted on the GAD Database and/or any other gender analysis tools;
The GFPS observe timely submission of the annual GPB and GAD AR to the Office of the Auditor in accordance with existing laws, rules and regulations;
Ensure that proper orientation on their duties and responsibilities be provided for newly assigned personnel particularly on appropriate laws, rules and regulation to enable them to properly perform their function; and
The GFPS equip themselves with necessary knowledge on the laws, rules and regulations related to their function for them to be able to deliver what is expected of them.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accountant to:
Expedite the gathering of relevant information necessary for the computation of depreciation for all Property, Plant, and Equipment (PPE) owned by the Municipality by coordinating with the concerned personnel such as the General Services Officer and the Municipal Engineer;
Recognize and record depreciation expense for all PPE in accordance with the standard;
Conduct an annual review of useful lives, residual values and depreciation methods; and
Ensure full disclosure of depreciation policies and computations in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Coordinate with the Municipal Engineer to verify the status of the projects with non-moving beginning balances and determine which projects have been completed;
Make the necessary adjusting entries to correctly reclassify completed projects from CIP to the appropriate PPE accounts, ensuring accurate financial reporting; and
Prepare and record the corresponding depreciation expenses for all reclassified completed projects to ensure proper expense recognition.

Additionally, require the Municipal Engineer to furnish the Municipal Accountant with a Certificate of Completion once a project is completed.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor the following:
Require the Accounting and Property Unit to continue the conduct of the preliminary activities as provided in Section 6.1 of COA Circular No. 2020-006. The documents or reports gathered shall be submitted to the Inventory Committee as a basis for the preparation of the  Physical   Inventory Plan;
Require the Inventory Committee to prepare the Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) and submit to COA the approved copy at least 10 calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities;
Direct the Inventory Committee to submit RPCPPE, in conformity with the form in Annex 49 of MNGAS, to the Municipal Accountant Office, the MGSO, and the Audit Team;
Require coordination of the Municipal Accountant, MGSO, and the Inventory Committee to reconcile the physical inventory of the PPE with the ledger cards and the property cards; and
Direct the inventory committee to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) which shall serve as the basis for the dropping from the books and expedite the disposal of the unserviceable properties in accordance with existing rules and regulations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Prepare an aging schedule of unliquidated cash advances and submit it to the audit team;
Remind all officials and employees of their obligation to liquidate cash advances on time and immediately return any excess funds intact, in accordance with COA Circular 97-002;
Closely monitor cash advances and issue demand letters to all accountable officers with outstanding balances, requiring them to promptly submit liquidation reports with supporting documents and immediately refund any unused funds;
Ensure that previous cash advances are fully liquidated and recorded in the books before granting additional advances to any officer or employee; and
Strictly enforce compliance with all applicable laws, rules, and regulations governing cash advances.

We recommended to the Management the following:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to transfer the current year’s unexpended/unobligated balance of the Local Risk Reduction and Management Fund to the Special Trust Fund under the account “Trust Liability- DRRM” in the Trust Fund books;
Require the Municipal Budget Officer to strengthen budget planning and monitoring to prevent errors and ensure that all disbursements are properly supported by appropriations.
Require the LDRRMO together with the members of the LDRRMC to identify and incorporate in the LDRRMFIP the PPAs to be funded from the previous years' unexpended QRF and DRRMF-MOOE which were transferred to the Special Trust Fund;
Submit justification for the variances noted between the SAAOB and Monthly Reports on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF;
Submit the lacking reports, supporting documents and disbursement vouchers to the audit team. Moving forward, strictly observe the reglementary period on the submission of the same as required under COA Circulars No. 2012-002 and 95-006.

We recommended and Management agreed to direct the Acting Municipal Accountant to:
Submit immediately the lacking disbursement vouchers and observe the prescribed period for the submission of DVs to COA;
Refrain from processing claims that are incomplete of supporting documents; and
Keenly observe the deadline set for the submission of trial balances and other financial reports as required under Sections 122 and 127 of PD 1445,                    Section 7.2.1 of COA Circular 2009-006, and pertinent provisions of COA Circular No. 95-006.

We recommend that the Management:
Require the Sangguniang Bayan to enact a resolution prescribing the policies and guidelines on the grant of donations/financial assistance containing the following:
Kind of financial assistance (medical, educational, funeral, etc.);
Approval limits for specific cases, including the frequency of grants to each individual;
Criteria in the granting of donation and the documentary requirements for each particular assistance;
All cases must be referred to the MSWDO for eligibility and evaluation and the case study report prepared must be made part of the supporting documents of the claim.
Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all payments are adequately and properly supported with the required documents to support the validity and regularity of claims.

Direct the Council to prepare the following reports:

Council’s Annual Work and Financial Plan are prioritized according to the needs for integration in the local development plan;
Local Development Plan for Children (LDPC);
Local Investment Plan for Children (LIPC);
Local State of Children’s Report.

To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommend that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

a. to conduct risk assessment; 

b. to identify critical processes and functions; 

c. to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 

d. to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis; 

e. to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and

f. to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We also recommend that Management should improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

2. Initiate the creation of the additional mandatory LDRRMO staff for administration and training, research and planning, and operations and warning through any or a combination of the following options as provided under NDRRMC-DILG-DBM-CSC Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2014-1 and R.A. No. 10121:

Designation or assignment of personnel of LGU to LDRRMO in concurrent capacities with their existing positions;
Reassignment of personnel of the LGU to the LDRRMO;
Full-time or part-time detail of existing personnel of other government agencies to the LDRRMO; and/or,
Transfer of existing vacant positions from other units to the LDRRMO. Accordingly, such vacant positions shall be abolished and positions appropriate to the LDRRMO shall be created.

Direct the Council to prepare the following reports:

Council’s Annual Work and Financial Plan are prioritized according to the needs for integration in the local development plan;
Local Development Plan for Children (LDPC);
Local Investment Plan for Children (LIPC);
Local State of Children’s Report.

We recommended that Management:

Immediately send a demand letter to the erring contractor as a final warning and require them to complete the works in accordance to the agreed terms and conditions of the contract without prejudice on the computation and imposition of liquidated damages to the said project;

In case of inexcusable failure or negligence of the erring contractor to comply on the above recommendation, the Chief Executive Office shall issue a Notice to Terminate Contract without prejudice to other courses of action and remedies available under the circumstances;

Recover/deduct the unperformed works amounting ₱1,746,397.18 from any payments due to the erring contractor;

Initiate take-over of the remaining work by administration or to consider rebidding through competitive bidding or any of the applicable alternative methods of procurement in accordance with R.A. 9184 and its IRR; and,

The Project Engineers to strictly monitor and supervise the infrastructure projects implemented by this Municipality to prevent time lag and delays.

We recommended that Management through the:
Municipal Accountant to prioritize GSIS and Pag-ibig deductions from payroll and not to resort to over-the-counter payments;
Municipal Accountant to reflect the loan deductions on payslips of the employees;
Municipal Treasurer to stop the practice of over-the-counter payments for mandatory payments and refuse accepting the same in behalf of the LGU; and,
Agency Authorized Officer to determine that any approval of loans be anchored on the ₱5,000-limit after the deduction of all mandatory contributions and loan amortizations.

We recommended to the GSO the following:
Locate the OR/CRs of the motor vehicles that have no ORs/CRs on file. If warranted, Management coordinate with the LTO for the issuance of a duplicate OR/CR of the vehicle;
Submit proof that the Nissan NV 350 Ambulance is intended to be donated by the Provincial Government of Zamboanga del Sur and that the transfer of vehicle registration from Pro-Life Health Care System Corporation to government is ongoing;
Implement the use of Temporary License Plates for all vehicles in accordance with the specifications laid out under the 2017 LTO Memorandum; and,
All of the vehicles be plainly marked “For Official Use Only” and also the name of the department/office such vehicle/s has been issued be indicated to properly identify responsibility on the vehicles used. Furthermore, ensure that expenditures for fuel charged against government funds are used for vehicles with the required markings.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Require the Accounting and Property Unit to conduct the required preliminary activities as provided in Section 6.1 of COA Circular No. 2020-006. The documents or reports gathered shall be submitted to the Inventory Committee as a basis for the preparation of the Physical Inventory Plan;
Require the Inventory Committee to prepare the Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) and submit to COA the approved copy at least 10 calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities;
Direct the Inventory Committee to (a) conduct a physical count of PPE by type and by department at the end of each year, and (b) submit RPCPPE, in conformity with the form in Annex 49 of MNGAS, to the Municipal Accountant Office, the MGSO, and the Audit Team;
Hire or augment additional personnel under the Municipal General Services Office and the Municipal Accounting Office to keep and maintain updated property ledger/stock cards for each class of PPE;
Direct the coordination of the Municipal Accountant, MGSO, and the Inventory Committee to reconcile the physical inventory of the PPE with the ledger cards and the property cards; and
Direct the inventory committee to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) which shall serve as the basis for the dropping from the books and expedite the disposal of the unserviceable properties in accordance with existing rules and regulations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Acting Municipal Accountant the following:
Reconcile the reciprocal accounts and effect adjustments to reflect the correct account balances and present reliable data pursuant to Section 111(2) of Presidential Decree No. 1445;
Conduct periodic reconciliation of the accounts with the concerned personnel to ensure that all transactions are properly and accurately recorded in the books of accounts;
Present the current and non-current portion of the Loans Payable – Domestic account; and
Prepare and submit supporting details/ schedules, and aging schedules and provide adequate and necessary disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements in order to provide information to the users and for a fair presentation of these accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Require the implementing offices or departments to properly coordinate with source agencies to secure copies of agreements previously entered into in relation to funds received;
Direct and enjoin all department heads concerned to monitor the implementation of all projects funded by other National Government Agencies, particularly those programs and activities relating to their offices in order to achieve the ultimate goals and objectives of the fund which is to promote general welfare and provide basic services to the constituents and furnish MOA, Trust Agreement, MOU or any document to the accounting office for proper recording;
Require to Acting Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the implementing units, to determine if the specific projects, for which the funds were transferred, were already implemented. Ensure that liquidation reports were already submitted and received by the source agencies for proper adjustment in the books;
Require the Municipal Accountant to verify with the source agencies whether to return or not the unexpended balance of the fund. If return is necessary, direct the Municipal Treasurer to return/remit to the source agencies such remaining balance. Otherwise, file a request to the source agencies for the authority to transfer the unexpended balance to the General Fund as provided under COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2023, if the disposition thereof has not been provided in the MOA, Trust Agreement or MOU;
Require the Acting Municipal Accountant to conduct regular and periodic evaluation, analysis, and validation of the existence of fund transfers and take up necessary adjusting entries for the misclassification of accounts, and to address any issues on dormant or idle accounts; and
Require the Acting Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to update and reconcile the balances in their books and prepare the utilization reports for the implemented projects duly approved by the Local Chief Executive in order to establish the correct balance of the Due to NGAs account in the financial statements.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor the following:
Require the Municipal Assessor to complete the updating of the Assessment Roll or secure from the Provincial Assessor’s Office the report of the updated/latest Revised Real Property Tax Assessment and furnish the same to the Municipal Treasurer as the latter’s basis for the collection of RPT and SET and for updating the Real Property Tax Account Register (RPTAR)/ Real Property Tax Index Card (RPTIC);
Require the Municipal Treasurer to submit the RPTAR/RPTIC to the Accounting Office at the beginning of the year as the basis of the Municipal Accountant to set up the correct amount of the RPT and SET Receivable accounts;
Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to reconcile their records and to make the appropriate adjustments to reflect the correct balances; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with the procedures provided under the NGAS Manual for LGU in the accounting of RPT/SET to fairly present the RPT and SET Receivable accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Direct the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) and Municipal Engineer to, at the beginning of the year, submit to this Office the list of all ongoing government Programs/Projects/ Activities (PPAs) and those that are to be implemented during the year;
Inform this Office within ten (10) days after the award of the infrastructure project or before the start of the program/activity that the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted;
Direct the Municipal Engineer to submit to this Office the monthly monitoring report on PPAs;
Submit geo-tagged photos of the above-mentioned government programs/projects/activities to the audit team; and
Ensure strict compliance with the general guidelines, reporting and monitoring of the information and publicity on Programs/Projects/Activities (PPAs) as imposed in COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 31, 2013, as amended by COA Circular No. 2015-006 dated August 20, 2015, and further amended by COA Circular No. 2016-003 dated August 16, 2016.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
Require the LDRRMO together with the members of the LDRRMC to identify and incorporate in the LDRRMFIP the PPAs to be funded from the previous years' unexpended QRF and DRRMF-MOOE which were transferred to the Special Trust Fund;
Require the Accounting Office to properly classify or sort the unspent portion by year and revert back to the General Fund for those that have already lapsed after the 5-year period;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to maintain a separate registry for the appropriations, allotments, and obligations of local disaster risk reduction and management fund specifically on 30 percent (30%) QRF, maintenance and other operating expenses and capital outlay;
Require the Management to create the mandatory support staff as mandated under Section 12.b of RA 10121 to ensure implementation of actions and measures related to disaster risk reduction and management;
Submit the lacking reports, supporting documents and disbursement vouchers to the audit team and strictly observe the reglementary period on the submission of the same as required under COA Circulars No. 2012-002 and 95-006; and
If possible, hire additional personnel in the accounting office to augment  workforce and facilitate the timely recording and preparation of financial reports.

We recommended to the management the following:
Require the collectors to remit their collections intact and daily to the Liquidating Officer or as soon as the collections reach P5,000.00;
Direct the Liquidating Officer to perform the verification functions of Collections and Accountable Forms required of her before signing the certification and receipt portion of all copies of the RCD; check the statement of AFs as to initial balances on hand, receipts, issues, and the ending balances on hand, make a physical count of AFs remaining in the custody of the Collector, and check against the new balances. She shall indicate her verification by affixing her signature at the back of the triplicate copy of the last OR issued;
Direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to acquire and implement ETRACS in the recording and reporting of collections of the Municipality; and
Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to exercise due diligence in the supervision of the accountable officers under her supervision as mandated under Section 104 of PD 1445.

We recommended to the management the following:
Direct the Accountable Officers under the Municipal Treasurer’s Officer to accomplish properly the Report of Collections and Deposits;
Direct the Accountable Officers to record daily his/her collections in the cashbook daily and in the order they occur;
Direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer and Collectors to reconcile the differences between the cashbook and the reports of RCD and it should be promptly cleared to ensure the accuracy and completeness of the recorded transactions; and
Direct the Accountable Officer to reconcile her records with the accounting at least at the end of each quarter.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Treasurer and Cashier to:
Stop the practice of using cash advance to pay for the Municipal’s operating expenses and activities, except those that are impractical to be paid in checks;
Ensure that the payments for supplies and materials are made thru checks and consider establishing a petty cash fund sufficient to pay for petty expenditures of the LGU;
Ensure that the purpose of cash advances is on the face of the disbursement vouchers and that are duly supported with complete documents at the time of grant of cash advances;
Exercise prudence and install necessary internal control in the utilization of government financial resources to ensure safeguard against unauthorized use and disposition thereof; and
Discontinue the practice of granting multiple cash advances to the Municipal Treasurer, Cashier and any accountable officer and ensure that the previous cash advance has been liquidated before granting additional cash advance.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
Procure consultancy services pursuant to the provisions in Republic Act No. 9184;
Reassess the hiring of consultants and determine their capabilities based on proven expertise;
Submit an explanation on the hiring of the consultants which is inconsonance with RA No. 9184;
Submit to COA within 5 days from execution of all of the contracts as required under Item 3.1.1 of COA Circular 2009-01;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure sufficient and complete documentation of consultancy payments pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-001.

We have recommended that Management:
Exhaust available options of transportation and exercising prudence to avoid hiring/paying for expensive vans, cars, aircraft, etc. except in meritorious cases and justified by prevailing circumstances;
Strictly observe the prescribed rules and regulations, and rates of expenses and allowances under Executive Order (EO) No. 77, otherwise such transactions will be subject to suspension or disallowance;
Discontinue the practice of allowing travel liquidations that are inconsistent with EO 77; and,
Require the accountable person/s provides a justification for this issue and submit it to our office subject for our review and assessment.

We recommended that Management:

Ensure that all deliveries are made in accordance with the terms and specifications indicated in the Contract/Purchase Order, hence adherence to the provisions of R.A. 9184 and other existing rules and regulations is strictly enjoined;

Enforce the concerned supplier to immediately deliver the undelivered procured books, otherwise impose liquidated damages in the amount equal to one-tenth of one percent (0.1%) of the cost of the unperformed portion for every day of delay;

The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile and compute variance in the case of similar and/or identical delivery of books that vary in prices, thus deducting the same from payment(s) due to the concerned supplier, if any.

Instruct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Acting Municipal Accountant and the Designated General Service Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

Instruct the Designated General Service Officer to render a Report on Local Road Network and Road Map; 

Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of the local roads under the jurisdiction of the municipality and render a Report on the Physical count of the Road Networks System; and

Instruct the Acting Municipal Accountant to record the municipal roads and its components based on the appraisal of the Municipal Engineer.

Appropriate fund for the titling of all land; 

Direct the Municipal Assessor̕ s Office to exert effort in titling the land owned by the Municipality; and

Require the Acting Municipal Accountant to submit the supporting documents for the procurement of land worth P1.5 million.

Instruct all Department heads to prepare and to submit their individual PPMPs showing the detailed list of goods or infrastructure projects to be procured during the coming year to the BAC Secretariat and to the Municipal Budget Officer who will ensure that amount involved are within budget; 

Require all members of the Bids and Awards Committee and the Head of the Procuring Entity to attend seminars/trainings that will improve their knowledge in the procurement; and

Direct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to prepare and submit regularly the Procurement Monitoring Report to the GPBB and Commission on Audit (COA) within fourteen (14) calendar days after end of each semester.

Create inventory committee; to prepare a timetable for the conduct of Physical Inventory including Local Road Network; to direct all Department Heads to coordinate with the Inventory Committee for a cohesive planning and to augment the workforce in the GSO specially during the conduct of physical inventory taking;

Instruct the Acting Municipal Accountant and Acting General Services Officer to maintain complete property ledger cards and property cards respectively for all PPE owned by the agency; and

Direct the Acting General Services Officer to maintain Subsidiary Records and Acknowledgment Receipt of Equipment (ARE) on all equipment as well as Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) for small items.

Require the designated Head of MEEDO or MAO to submit the financial statements of the waterworks;

Require the Acting Municipal Accountant to prepare necessary adjusting entries to record the assets, liabilities and equity of the waterworks in the LGU and to maintain subsidiary ledgers and financial statements necessary in planning and evaluating the performance of the waterworks; and

Install or designate a new Head of Office of the MEEDO to oversee the operations of the waterworks and other economic ventures of the LGU.

Ensure that programs, projects and activities are responsive to the needs of the children and pursuant to those identified in the Local Development Plan for Children (LDPC);

Direct the Council to prepare the following reports:

Council’s Annual Work and Financial Plan prioritized according to needs for integration in the local development plan;
Local Development Plan for Children (LDPC); 
Local Investment Plan for Children (LIPC);
Local State of Children’s Report.

We recommended that the MSWDO submit to the Audit Team a copy of the following documents:
Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) between the Municipality and the DSWD pursuant to Section III.A.1 of DSWD MC No. 2020-006;
Photocopy of valid IDs with specimen signatures of the 43 beneficiaries which were lacking in the cash assistance payrolls;
For each beneficiary, a copy of updated SAC Form, photo taken during actual receipt, and specific documentary requirements as enumerated under Section VII.A.1 of DSWD MC No. 2020-009 or a certification from the barangay that the beneficiary is in need of assistance from DSWD, as the case may be; and
Reasonable explanation why the lacking documents were not submitted to the Audit Team and why some claimants were allowed to receive the cash assistance even without a proper authorization letter.

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant henceforth, ensure that cash assistance payrolls under all social amelioration programs are duly supported with complete documentation in accordance with pertinent DSWD circulars and other related issuances.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to direct the following:
The creation of Inventory Committee composed of adequate number of members, with at least one member each from the Municipal Accounting Office and General Services Office;
The Inventory Committee (a) to conduct physical count of PPE by type and by department at the end of each year, and (b) to submit RPCPPE, in conformity with the form in Annex 49 of MNGAS, to the Municipal Accountant Office, the MGSO, and the Audit Team
The Municipal General Services Office (a) to keep and maintain updated property cards for each class of PPE, and (b) to reconcile with the ledger cards maintained by the Municipal Accountant;
The coordination of the Municipal Accountant, MGSO, and the Inventory Committee to reconcile the physical inventory of the PPE with the ledger cards and the property cards;
The Municipal Accountant to compute the depreciation on the subject accounts and make the necessary adjustment on the affected accounts; and
Refrain from designating two functions in one person.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Appropriate fund for the titling of all land;
Direct the Municipal Assessor’s Office to facilitate the preparation of documentary requirements to secure the Transfer Certificate of Title of the land owned by the Municipality;
Require the Acting Municipal Accountant to submit the supporting documents for the purchase of land and ensure that future procurement of land should not be made through cash advance;
The Municipal Accountant to ensure that the Land accounts recorded in the books, which were not supported with TCT and other legal documents of ownership, should be properly disclosed in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer and the concerned officers and employees to liquidate their outstanding cash advances immediately;
Require the Acting Municipal Accountant to strictly monitor the liquidation and refund of cash advances.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the Liquidating Officer/Acting Municipal Treasurer to ensure that all her collections as well as those remitted to her will be deposited intact and daily or in the frequency prescribed by regulation;
Direct the Collector/Cashier to turn over her collections intact and daily to the Liquidating Officer in the frequency required under existing regulation.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to require the Acting Municipal Treasurer the following:
Stop the practice of using cash advance to pay for the Municipality’s operating expenses and activities;
Ensure that payments for suppliers are made thru checks and consider establishing a petty cash fund to address petty expenditures of the LGU;
Ensure that the purposes of cash advances are on the face of the disbursement vouchers and that are duly supported with complete documents at the time of grant of cash advances;
Discontinue the practice of granting multiple cash advances to the Acting Municipal Treasurer and ensure that her previous cash advance has been liquidated before granting additional cash advance; and
Submit all Report of Cash Disbursements for CY 2021.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive:
Instruct the BAC to prioritize and submit all lacking supporting documents of the subject contracts immediately and to submit prospective contracts within 5 days upon their perfection in accordance with COA Circular 2009-001;
Invite in writing a representative of the COA and other two (2) observers as provided in the Section 13 of R.A. No. 9184 in all stages of the procurement process;
Require the BAC to strengthen the evaluation process of bids and post-qualification of bidders;
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to require the contractor to post the required performance security of all projects to ensure the validity and faithful performance by the winning bidder of its obligation under the contract;
Direct the BAC Secretariat to publish in the Phil-GEPS website and in the agency website the Notices of Award and Notices to Proceed for the procurement done through public bidding and all instances of alternative modes of procurement, except for contracts with ABC of ₱50,000.00 and below;
Advise management headed by the Local Chief Executive to revisit the internal control policies over LGU operations to identify and address these recurring lapses over submission of contracts; and
Observe strictly the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184 to ensure adherence to the principles of transparency, competitiveness and public monitoring.

Recommendations:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal  Treasurer to furnish the Chief Accountant  a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible  as the basis for establishing the Real Property Tax Receivables/Special Education Tax Receivables at the beginning for the year;
Send notices/demand letters to the concerned taxpayers who had not paid their real property taxes directing them to pay and settle their obligations.

Direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to ensure that all her collections as well as those remitted to her will be deposited intact and daily or in the frequency prescribed by regulation;

Direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to delegate the liquidating function to other Revenue Collectors or Cashier to reduce her workload; and

Direct the Acting Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer to set a specific date on a monthly basis when to reconcile their records without delay so that any discrepancy noted in the process could be corrected immediately.

Require the BAC Secretariat to transmit all contracts pending for submission immediately and to ensure that prospective contracts will be submitted within five (5) days after the perfection of the contract; 

Direct the Acting Municipal Accountant to ensure that ABC and Inspection Report are attached in the disbursement vouchers and that retention money are deducted in every progress billings; and

Require the Municipal Engineer to prepare Certificate of Project Completion and Certificate of Acceptance for completed projects and to request for its technical inspection from COA.

Direct the designated MDRRMO and Acting Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit a revised Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF enumerating therein all sources of funds and disbursements expended for calamity in CY 2020;

Direct the designated MDRRMO and Municipal Accountant to submit Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF report on or before the 15th day after the end of each month; and

Direct the Municipal Budget Officer and Acting Municipal Accountant to ensure that available funds for calamity are based on the regular sources of the LGU.

Instruct the Acting Municipal Accountant to approve and process only those disbursement vouchers supported with complete and valid documentations and approvals;
Augment the working force under the Accounting Office with great consideration on the competency and qualification; and

Require the Municipal Accounting Office and Municipal Treasurer’s Office to maintain logbook to record all incoming/outgoing documents/reports.

Require the Municipal Planning Development Coordinator (MPDC) to provide an explanation and identify the difficulties in the preparation of Annual Investment Plan;

Direct all Department Heads of LGU and Focal Persons to strictly observe the time frame prescribed in the preparation of annual budget; and

Require the Municipal Budget Officer to review and ensure that forms of the annual budget are in accordance with the latest prescribed forms and that computations in the report are all accurate.

Require the concerned employees to submit the lacking documents;

Instruct the Municipal HRMO to make necessary adjustment in the leave cards of officers or employees whose monetization were deducted from the sick leave instead of vacation leave and to prepare Summary of Leave credit balances of all employees at the end of the year for employees’ information and ready reference;  and 

Refrain from utilizing the budget for Terminal Leave Pay for payment of monetization as the two accounts have different purpose.

Direct the Acting Municipal Accountant the following:

Prepare adjusting entry to close the account Trust Liability – DRRMF amounting to ₱3,719,254 under general fund books; 

Reconcile and determine the unexpended/unobligated balance of the Quick Response Fund (QRF) and the DRRMF-MOOE and eventually prepare the necessary entry to recognize the trust liability under the Trust Fund books.

Ensure timely implementation of all 20% development projects;

Require the MPDC to provide specific target dates of implementation of the PPAs and the related target schedule for each procurement activities in order to ensure timely implementation of projects; and

Direct the Acting Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Budget Officer to provide sufficient allocation in the General Fund for operating requirements of the LGU-Magsaysay Managed Water System (LMMWS) and to ascertain proper charging of expenses to the 20% DF.

Impose strict compliance with PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01 and to ensure that GAD Plan and Budget are prepared and submitted to DILG for their review and approval.;

Require the GAD Focal Person and MPDC to conduct gender mainstreaming to identify the appropriate activities responsive to the needs of the LGU constituents; establish and maintain a GAD Database in implementing the Magna Carta for Women which helps in formulating GAD-related activities based on information gathered; and prepare and submit Annual GAD Accomplishment Report including all its supporting documents as prescribed under DILG-NEDA Joint Circular No. 2013-01; and

Require the Municipal Budget Officer to ensure that programs, projects and activities included in the GAD Plan and Budget are in accordance with the JMC.

Direct the Municipal Treasurer, Cashier and Revenue Collectors to – 

Maintain a cashbook for each accountable form per fund and for each type of cash advances per fund;

Record daily their transactions in the cashbook in ink and in the order they occur;

Balance, rule and close at the end of the day their cashbook and foot and close the books at the end of each month; and

Reconcile their cashbook with the accounting records regularly or at least once in every quarter to establish the correct balance of accountability of the AO at the earliest time possible. Any account found unrecorded can be easily traced and the necessary corrections/recording can be effected immediately.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to create a subsidiary ledger for each revenue collecting officer.

Refrain from implementing projects by administration;

Provide fund counterparts on projects implemented from National Government Agencies as stipulated in the MOA;

Request for the inspection of all completed projects either by contract or by admin addressed to the COA audit team and attach the contracts and other supporting documents for auditorial and technical review, so that inspection by COA technical services will be facilitated; and

Submit the following documents to enable us to make a decision in audit:

Contract of Service of laborers hired either by job-order or through the pakyaw contracting system, Accomplishment Reports and DTRs or Certificate of Service and Payrolls duly signed;

Justification on late purchase of construction signage; and Program of Work and Detailed Estimate of the project.

