Implement the “No Liquidation, No Cash Advance” policy.  Discontinue the practice of granting new cash advances to disbursing officer and/or officers and employees while there are still unliquidated cash advances; 

Return or refund immediately to the collecting officer the any cash advance which was no longer needed or had not been used immediately;

Monitor closely the immediate liquidation of all cash advances;

Deduct on a staggered basis an appropriate and reasonable amount from the monthly salary of concerned officers and employees the unliquidated cash advances; 

Discontinue granting cash advances for salaries and terminal pay; 

Reconcile the difference or variance between the Schedule and the General Ledger of  Cash Advances of Officials and Employees; and

Comply strictly with Section 89 of Presidential Decree 1445 otherwise filing of malversation charge of concerned accountable officer shall be enforced.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, through the:

Local School Board               (a) prepare the SEF Budget in the prescribed SEF Budget Preparation Form No. 1;          (b) provide details of each budgetary allocation and refrain from making lump-sum budget; and (c) observe the timely preparation, submission and approval of the Annual SEF Budget as prescribed by DepEd/DBM/DILG Joint Circular No. 1, Series of 2017;

Bids and Awards Committee conduct meticulous procurement planning and proper determination of the mode of procurement to be used which must be indicated in the Annual Procurement Plan;

Municipal Accountant           (a) verify the regularity and completeness of supporting documents to establish the validity and legality of the disbursements pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-001; and (b) prepare the quarterly Report on SEF Utilization using SEF Budget Accountability Form 1 as prescribed by DepED/DBM/DILG JC No. 1, Series of 2017; and

Concerned accountable officers submit complete and proper liquidation reports and supporting documents to ensure that cash advances were used in accordance with the purpose for which it was granted.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive to - 

Direct the Municipal Accountant to provide depreciation expense for all the depreciable assets for CY 2017 and to effect any adjustment on erroneous posting/entries regarding the accounts.

Designate a permanent property officer/custodian and constitute an inventory committee to conduct the physical inventory taking of all property, plant and equipment of the Municipality including the inventory items;

Direct the property officer as well as the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain reports/records like the RPCI, RPCPPE, Supplies Ledger Cards, Stock Cards and Property Cards for the proper monitoring of properties purchased, donated, transferred or disposed of;

Direct the property officer to maintain Subsidiary Records and Acknowledgment Receipt of Equipment (ARE) on all equipment as well as Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) for small items;

Prepare and reconcile the Inventory Report with the Accounting Records to present fairly the PPE account in the financial statement; 

Conduct a proper valuation of all PPEs not recorded as well as a report of all unserviceable properties for appropriate appraisal of the scrap value if there is, and for proper disposal; and

Investigate any discrepancy or loss and immediately report the same to the COA for appropriate action.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Accountant and the In-Charge of Office (ICO) – Municipal Treasurer to exert extra effort in identifying the accountabilities of each former Municipal Treasurer on the collections that remained undeposited for more than two (2) decades. Upon determination, the Municipal Accountant shall prepare the necessary Journal Entry Vouchers to reclassify the undeposited balance of former Municipal Treasurers from Cash – Local Treasury to a proper Receivable account for fair presentation in the Statement of Financial Position.
Likewise, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accountant to:
Make the necessary adjustments for the: (i) noted errors in recording in the Cash – Local Treasury account amounting to P1,040,501.15; (ii) long outstanding cash advances of employees and officers recorded under the Accounts Payable totaling P2,875,102.12; and (iii) reclassification of the Loans Payable – Domestic account from Non-Current Liability to Current Liability for the fair and accurate presentation of the affected accounts in the Statement of Financial Position;
Identify the valid book reconciling items and prepare the necessary adjustments in the Cash in Bank Local Currency Current Account for the fair presentation of the Financial Statements;
Verify the validity and existence of the Accounts Payable and determine whether these are still valid and enforceable especially those that have been dormant for two years or more. After which, notify the concerned payees of their outstanding claims, but, if found to be without valid claim, proper reversion should be made to the Unappropriated Surplus in the General Fund for fair and accurate presentation of the account balances in the financial statements; and
Analyze the unreconciled balances of the Due from and Due to Other Funds account, prepare a reconciliation statement therein and make the necessary adjustments in the books for the affected funds for fair and accurate presentation in the Statement of Financial Position in order to provide information that is reliable and relevant to the users of the Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor: (a) ensure that all procurement activities undertaken by the Municipality is strictly in accordance with the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 particularly during the bid evaluation and post-qualification phase for proper evaluation and assessment of the eligibility, legal, technical and financial capacities of the prospective bidders; (b) see to it that projects are completed in accordance with the approved plans and specifications before issuing the Certificates of Acceptance and the approval of claims for payment to safeguard government funds and property from loss and/or wastage; (c) cause the contractor to refund the cost of the uninstalled signboards/billboards; and (d) ask the cooperation of the Punong Barangay of Barangay Alibog in resolving conflicts among residents of the two Sitios to effectively benefit the end users of the SALINTUBIG project.
We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
BAC and its Technical Working Group (TWG) to immediately submit the lacking documents to arrive at a decision in audit and henceforth ensure that perfected contracts are properly and completely documented before submitting the same to this Office;
BAC to: (i) invite, in addition to the representative of the COA, at least two observers in all stages of the procurement process, namely: the Pre-Bid Conference, Bid Opening and Post-qualification phase, pursuant to Section 13.1 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; (ii) post in the PhilGEPS and in any conspicuous places within the premises of the LGU copies of the Notices of Award, Approved Contracts and Notices to Proceed within the prescribed period pursuant to Sections 37.1.6 and 37.4.2 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; and (iii) be vigilant in all stages of the procurement process particularly during the bid evaluation and post-qualification phase for proper evaluation and assessment of the eligibility, legal, technical and financial capacities of the prospective bidders;
Municipal Engineer, in future projects, to: (i) prepare the ABC in the format prescribed under DPWH Department Order No. 197 s. 2016; (ii)closely monitor the project implementations and ensure that it is in accordance with the approved plans and specifications before issuing Inspection Reports for 100% work accomplishments; (iii) see to it that changes in the original plans and designs to suit the actual conditions, if any, must be done after the Change/Extra Work Order is prepared and approved by the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Mayor, respectively, in compliance with Item 3.1 Annex E of the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184; and (iv) ensure that project billboards are duly installed for all projects in compliance with COA Circular No. 2013-004;
Designated focal person for the SALINTUBIG project to fast track the submission of lacking documents specifically the permits and licenses to the DILG-RO for the release of the second tranche of the subproject allocation; and
Municipal Accountant to submit immediately the lacking supporting documents in the claims for advance/progress/final billings and henceforth ensure that all claims are duly supported with proper and complete supporting documents required under Sections 9.1.1.3, 9.1.1.4 and 9.1.3.1 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 before processing for payment.

We recommended that the:
Municipal Treasurer submit an explanation why she prepared the check while the DV was not signed by the Municipal Accountant;
Municipal Accountant submit an explanation why she issued the advice of checks issued but did not sign the disbursement voucher; Municipal Mayor and Municipal Treasurer jointly submit an explanation why the disbursements were approved and the checks were issued, despite the lack of signature of the Municipal Accountant on the disbursement vouchers;
Municipal Mayor, in coordination with the officers and employees concerned, cause the immediate submission of the documentary deficiencies identified in this AOM; and
Municipal Engineer submit a report on the status of implementation of the Salintubig Projects as of the date of expiration of their contract time.
According to the Municipal Accountant, she did not sign the vouchers because she did not have time to review the transactions. The Management has not yet provided a complete explanation on this matter, but agreed to take action on the audit recommendations.

We recommended that the Municipal Treasurer:
inform the Provincial Treasurer that the provision for granting discount on RPT as provided under the New Revenue Code of Palawan is in conflict with Section 246 of RA No. 7160, Article 342 of the IRR of RA No. 7160 and Section 177 of the LTOM;
propose to the Provincial Treasurer the issuance of a revised Notice of Payment for CY 2018 or any other means to disseminate information to taxpayers, clarifying that RPT payments made during the first quarter of the year are not considered “advanced” but instead “prompt” and subject only to 10% discount;
collect the amount of under-collection of RPT due from taxpayers for CY 2018 but only after providing them clear and sufficient information on the correct discounts and taxes due, notwithstanding the issuance of a Notice of Delinquency in accordance with Section 254 of RA No. 7160 and Article 345 of its IRR; and
henceforth, adhere to Article 342 of the IRR of RA No. 7160 in granting discounts on RPT payments.
The Municipal Treasurer commented that the Provincial Government of Palawan has already been notified about this audit observation. Consequently, the Office of the Sangguniang Panlalawigan issued Provincial Ordinance No. 2015, series of 2018, which was approved on September 4, 2018. The said Ordinance amended Section 72 of its Revenue Code to conform with Section 251 of RA No. 7160. The Municipal Treasurer said that she already applied the said amendment in CY 2019 and granted only 10% discount for prompt payments.

